337. tibi marks the change on Andromache’s part from explanation to question. By qui renti, quae fata, she means to ask whether Aeneas’ presence was accidental, and due to pressure of weather, or whether he had been directed to the land by fate.

338. appulit is a nautical term, ‘to bring a ship to land.’ Compare Book i. l. 377.

. 339. quid. Some such verb as facit must be supplied. We should say, ‘What of the boy Ascanius?’ Compare Georq. iii. 258 Quid iuvenis?

superat : equivalent to superest: ‘ to survive.’

vescitur aura: a Lucretian phrase (Lucr. v. 857 vesci vitalibus auris), found also in Book i. l. 546 si rescitur azo-a Aetherea. Vergil implies that the air is the source of life, so that there is no need to follow Munro in taking vesci 2 ‘use’ 3 but we may translate ‘ feeds on.'
